<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-02T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-02T02:00:00-05:00" n="250" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d250">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/432:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-02T15:00:00+08:00">November 2, 1929—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 2—1:20 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>951. Following from American Consul at Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 1, noon. October 30th three Soviet aircraft bombed
                                    outskirts of Fuchin which unconfirmed rumor states now in Soviet
                                    hands. Communication between Fuchin and Lahasusu cut, so
                                    conditions in latter place unknown. It is reported that Soviet
                                    gunboats are in the vicinity of Fuchin, probably in search of
                                    grain barges. Early this morning freight train blown up on east
                                    line railway, resulting in derailment of locomotive and five
                                    cars.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>